ADF Full Form

ADF = Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test

Let's break the name into parts:

1. Dickey-Fuller

The test was developed by two statisticians:

David Dickey
Wayne Fuller

They introduced the original Dickey-Fuller (DF) Test.

2. Augmented

"Augmented" means:

👉 Improved
👉 Enhanced
👉 Extended

The original Dickey-Fuller test worked for simple time series.

Researchers later added extra lag terms to handle more complex data.

So:

Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) = Improved Dickey-Fuller Test

Who Invented It?

The original Dickey-Fuller test was proposed by:

David Dickey
Wayne Fuller

Both were from the United States (USA).

Which Year?

Their famous research paper was published in:

📅 1979

Paper title:

📖 Distribution of the Estimators for Autoregressive Time Series with a Unit Root

This paper introduced the Dickey-Fuller test and laid the foundation for the later ADF test.

Why Was It Invented?

Before 1979, statisticians needed a reliable way to answer:

"Is this time series stationary or non-stationary?"

Examples:

Stock prices
Weather data
Sales data
Economic indicators

Dickey and Fuller created a statistical test to detect the presence of a unit root.

Unit Root Means

A series keeps drifting over time and is generally:

❌ Non-stationary

Example:

| Year | House Price |
| ---- | ----------: |
| 2021 |          40 |
| 2022 |          50 |
| 2023 |          65 |
| 2024 |          80 |

The values keep moving upward.
=========

Simple Story Behind the Name

Imagine:

👨‍🔬 David Dickey + 👨‍🔬 Wayne Fuller create a test in 1979.

The test checks:

"Is the data stable or wandering?"

Later, statisticians improved it by adding extra lag terms.

So the improved version became:

Augmented + Dickey + Fuller = ADF

=========

ADF stands for Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test. It is an enhanced version of the Dickey-Fuller test, 
originally developed by American statisticians David Dickey and Wayne Fuller in 1979. 
It is used to check whether a time series is stationary or contains a unit root (non-stationary).

